e Development and First Nations in Alberta and Ontario -- tThe Changing Landscape of Métis Governance -- tMétis-Provincial-Federal Relations: Building Multilevel Governance From the Bottom Up -- tR V. DANIELS: Jurisdiction and Government Obligations to Non-Status Indians and Métis -- tSocial Policy Governance: Moving Beyond Jurisdictional Boundaries? -- tKelowna’s Uneven Legacy: Aboriginal Poverty and Multilevel Governance in Canada -- tCan an Emergency Response Translate into Practicable Policy? Post-Flood Provincial–First Nations Housing in Alberta -- tOn-Reserve Schools: An Underperforming “Non-System” -- tProvincial Aboriginal Policy in Changing Times -- tOntario’s Approach to Aboriginal Governance -- tRethinking Provincial-Aboriginal Relations in British Columbia -- tConcluding Thoughts -- tConcluding Thoughts -- tQueen’s Policy Studies Recent Publications0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTraditionally associated with the federal government, Aboriginal policy has arguably become a far more complex reality. With or without formal self-government, Aboriginal communities and nations are increasingly assertive in establishing their own authority in areas as diverse as education, land management, the administration of justice, family and social services, and housing. The 2013 State of the Federation volume gathers experts and practitioners to discuss the contemporary dynamics, patterns, and challenges of Aboriginal multilevel governance in a wide range of policy areas. Recent court decisions on Aboriginal rights, notably on the duty to consult, have forced provincial and territorial governments to develop more sustained relationships with Aboriginal organizations and governments, especially in the management of lands and resources. Showing that Aboriginal governance is, more than ever, a multilevel reality, contributors address questions such as: What are the challenges in negotiating and implementing these bilateral and trilateral governance agreements? Are these governance arrangements conducive to real and sustained Aboriginal participation in the policy process? Finally, what are the implications of these various developments for Canadian federalism and for the rights and status of Aboriginal peoples in relation to the Canadian federation?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxGovernment relationsy1934-. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxPolitics and government. 0aIndians of North America--Canada--Politics and government. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxGovernment relationsy1934-. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxGovernment relations. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxPolitics and government. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aAlcantara, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelanger, Yale D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoates, Ken, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraik, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubois, Janique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGottfred, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrlbacher-Fox, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuneau, André, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKing, Hayden, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarocque, Florence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaunay, David de, econtributor.4c